In [[botany]], '''perennation''' is the ability of [[organism]]s, particularly [[plant]]s, to survive from one [[Germination|germinating]] season to another, especially under unfavourable conditions such as drought or winter. It typically involves development of a '''perennating organ''', which stores enough [[nutrient]]s to sustain the organism during the unfavourable season, and develops into one or more new plants the following year. Common forms of perennating organs are [[storage organs]] (e.g. [[tuber]]s and [[rhizome]]s), and [[bud]]s. Perennation is closely related with [[vegetative reproduction]], as the organisms commonly use the same organs for both survival and reproduction.<ref>{{cite book|title=Practical Advanced Biology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oAFiCHdrEAYC&pg=PA213 |first1=Tim |last1=King |first2=Michael |last2=Reiss |page=213 |publisher=Nelson Thornes |year=2001 |isbn=9780174483083}}</ref>
